# Fixture (ii): diamond re-enqueue / Delta_D discipline stress.
#
# Diamond over `link`: 1 -> 2 -> 4 (short arm via node 2) AND
# 1 -> 3 -> 4 -> 5 (longer arm via node 3, one hop further to node 5).
# Also a SEPARATE direct short-circuit: 2 -> 5, so node 5 is reachable
# BOTH as a 3-hop derivation from base(1) via 1->3->4->5 AND as a 2-hop
# derivation via 1->2->5. This means q(5) has two derivations of
# DIFFERENT round-depth from the same base(1) retraction: the claim
# round that overdeletes q(4) (arrived at via the LONG arm, round 3) can
# try to re-fire q(5)'s removal via link(4,5) in round 4, while q(5) was
# ALREADY claimed for overdeletion back in round 3 via link(2,5) (q(2) is
# claimed in round 2). If OVERDELETE fires over the raw drained queue
# rather than the per-round claimed frontier Delta_D, q(5)'s removal can
# be double-processed (re-derivation-counted twice) when it is
# re-enqueued by BOTH q(2)'s round-2 claim (already retired) and q(4)'s
# round-3 claim -- a wrong Delta_D discipline either double-decrements
# C_r for q(5) (driving it to -1, a commit-assert SIGABRT under debug) or
# leaves q(5) present when it must be fully gone.
#
# Batch 1: seed the diamond links (never retracted).
# Batch 2: seed base(1); q_out must reach {1,2,3,4,5}.
# Batch 3: retract base(1); q_out must become EMPTY (no other base fact
#   supports any node -- this is a pure firewall-free cascade, so any
#   wrong double-counting either strands a phantom row or asserts).
batch
+ link 1 2
+ link 1 3
+ link 2 4
+ link 3 4
+ link 4 5
+ link 2 5
end

batch
+ base 1
end

batch
- base 1
end
